Question: What is the confirmation period for an appointment to a managerial
  position at a higher salary band?
Example answer: The confirmation period shall be six months. Where the member of staff
  is prevented by illness, accident, maternity or, in exceptional
  circumstances, special leave from performing their duties for a
  period of more than one month, the appointing authority may extend
  the confirmation period accordingly. (ECB Staff Rules, page 43)
Predicted answer: - Confirmation period: Six months. - Applicability: Appointments to a
  managerial position at a higher salary band and a first appointment
  in a managerial position at the same salary band. -
  Assessment/criteria: During the six-month period the appointing
  authority assesses performance against the competencies and skills
  required for the position; a performance report is prepared and used
  for the confirmation review. - External assessment: Appointments
  made outside a selection procedure generally require an external
  leadership-skills assessment unless the appointment is for three
  months or less or the appointee has a documented positive track
  record of managerial performance at the same level. - Extensions:
  The appointing authority may extend the six-month confirmation
  period where the member is prevented from performing duties by
  illness, accident, maternity or, in exceptional circumstances,
  special leave for more than one month. - Decision authority: The
  appointing authority takes non-confirmation decisions following the
  review; who prepares the review report depends on the salary
  band/position. - References: ECB Staff Rules, Articles 1a.3.8–1a.3.9
  (p.43); ECB Conditions of Employment (p.6).
