  Executive Board, may waive, extend or otherwise decide on
  probationary matters (Arts. 2.1.1–2.1.3).  - When probation can be
  extended:   - If the probationer is prevented from performing duties
  by illness, accident, maternity or (in exceptional circumstances)
  special leave for more than one month, the Chief Services Officer
  may extend the probationary period accordingly (Art. 2.1.2).   - In
  exceptional circumstances the Chief Services Officer may extend the
  probationary period up to a maximum of 12 months; alternatively the
  Chief Services Officer may extend up to 12 months and assign the
  probationer to another function (Art. 2.1.2(a)–(b)).  - Performance-
  related outcomes and notice:   - For inadequate performance or
  suitability during probation the Chief Services Officer may
  terminate the contract, giving one month’s notice (Art. 2.1.3).   -
  The probationer may resign at any time during probation, giving one
  month’s notice; the Chief Services Officer may release the
  probationer from actual duty during the notice period (Art. 2.1.3).
  - Procedural formalities: decision-making competence is attributed
