Example answer: Teleworking shall not exceed a maximum of 10 consecutive working days.
  This limit applies both within and across calendar months, and also
  applies where teleworking is combined with leave; leave shall not
  interrupt the consecutiveness. (ECB Staff Rules, page 84)
Predicted answer: - Maximum consecutive teleworking days: Teleworking shall not exceed a
  maximum of 10 consecutive working days. - Conditions / measurement:
  - The limit is measured in working days.   - Teleworking may be
  authorised as either a half working day or a full working day; the
  consecutive-days limit is expressed in working days.   - The 10-day
  consecutiveness applies both within and across calendar months.   -
  Where teleworking is combined with leave, leave does not interrupt
  the consecutiveness (i.e., the count continues). - Exceptions: The
  same 10-consecutive-working-day limit applies in exceptional
  circumstances or cases of force majeure (including teleworking from
  locations inside or outside the Union). - Policy reference: ECB
  Staff Rules, Article 5.1bis (see Article 5.1bis.4 and the
  exceptional‑circumstances paragraph), pp.83–84, 87.
