Question: I have been suspended pending an investigation and the Executive Board
  has decided to withhold part of my basic salary. Is there a floor
  below which my income cannot fall?
Example answer: During suspension, the part of the basic salary withheld may not
  exceed half, and the staff member's income may not be less than the
  minimum subsistence figure. That minimum subsistence figure is
  defined as the basic salary of a staff member in salary band A at
  step 1. (ECB Conditions of Employment, pages 17, 23)
Predicted answer: Short answer - Yes. The Executive Board can withhold part of basic
  salary during suspension but may not withhold more than one half
  (50%) of basic salary, and the member’s income may not be reduced
  below the “minimum subsistence figure” in Article 35 of the
  Conditions of Employment. (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.23; ECB
  Staff Rules, pp.128–129.) - The precise monetary amount of the
  Article 35 floor and which pay elements are included in the “member
  of staff’s income” (basic salary only or also allowances,
  rent/education, employer social-security contributions, etc.) were
  not provided in the material retrieved and must be obtained from the
  official text of Article 35 or from HR. (Source: observation_0.)
  Key points from the retrieved material 1. Legal floor and cap on
  withholding    - Maximum withheld = 50% of the member’s basic
  salary.    - Income cannot be reduced below the “minimum subsistence
  figure” set out in Article 35 of the Conditions of Employment.
  (Conditions of Employment, p.23.)  2. Formal requirements for the
  suspension decision    - The suspension decision must state whether
  full salary continues or a part is withheld and specify the amount
  withheld.    - The Executive Board takes the suspension decision (or
  the Chief Services Officer on its behalf for staff at salary band I
  or below). The member must be heard before the decision except in
  exceptional circumstances. (Conditions of Employment, p.23; Staff
  Rules, 8.4.1, 8.4.3–8.4.4, pp.128–129.)  3. Procedural safeguards,
  duration and remedies    - Hearing: the member should be heard
  before the suspension decision, save exceptional circumstances.    -
  Reimbursement if no final decision: if within nine months of
  suspension no final decision has been taken — or if no measure other
  than a written warning or a written reprimand has been adopted — the
  ECB shall reimburse the amount of salary withheld. (Conditions of
  Employment, p.23.)    - If the Executive Board (or Chief Services
  Officer on its behalf) dismisses with effect from the day of
  suspension, amounts paid during suspension are retained by the
  member. (Staff Rules, 8.4.2, p.129.)    - Appeal routes and time-
  limits: disciplinary measures may be challenged within two months by
  appeal to the President if imposed by the Director General Human
  Resources or their Deputy; measures taken by the Executive Board,
  the President, or the Chief Services Officer (acting on behalf of
  the Executive Board) may be challenged within two months by way of
  appeal to the Court of Justice of the European Union. Observations
  on the Disciplinary Committee’s opinion must be submitted within 15
  calendar days from transmission. (Staff Rules, 8.3.24; 8.4.1–8.4.4,
  pp.128–129.)  4. What the retrieved material did NOT provide    -
  The numeric value of the “minimum subsistence figure” in Article 35.
  - A clear breakdown of which remuneration components count toward
  the “member of staff’s income” for the Article 35 floor (e.g.,
  whether family/child allowances, rent/education allowances or
  employer social-security contributions are included).  Recommended
  immediate steps (practical actions and who to contact) 1. Ask for
  the formal suspension decision in writing (if you have not received
  it): request the document stating whether full salary continues or
  how much is withheld and the legal basis. (Conditions of Employment,
  p.23.) 2. Contact Director General Human Resources (or their Deputy)
  immediately and request:    - The calculation showing how the
  withheld amount was determined.    - Confirmation in writing that
  your resulting income complies with the Article 35 minimum
  subsistence figure (and an explanation of which pay elements were
  included in the calculation). (Staff Rules, 8.4.3–8.4.4,
  pp.128–129.) 3. Preserve evidence: keep copies of the suspension
  decision, all communications, and pay statements showing amounts
  paid/withheld. 4. Note and prepare for deadlines:    - Reimbursement
  trigger: if there is no final decision (or only a written
  warning/reprimand) within nine months from suspension, prepare to
  claim reimbursement of withheld pay. (Conditions of Employment,
  p.23.)    - Appeal deadlines: preserve the right to challenge
  disciplinary measures — observe the two‑month appeal time limits set
  out in the Staff Rules and the 15‑day period for observations on the
  Disciplinary Committee’s opinion. (Staff Rules, pp.128–129.) 5. Seek
  advice: use any internal advisory resources (HR clarification, staff
  representation/union where applicable) and consider early legal
  advice if you contemplate appeal or other proceedings.  If you need
  the exact monetary floor or a definitive list of protected pay
  components - Request an official calculation and the text of Article
  35 from DG HR (the retrieved excerpts did not include the Article 35
  figure or the breakdown of included pay components). The DG HR will
  provide the official monetary figure and clarify which remuneration
  elements are counted.  References (from the material retrieved) -
  ECB Conditions of Employment, p.23 (rules on suspension, withholding
  up to 50%, minimum subsistence figure, reimbursement after nine
  months). - ECB Staff Rules, pp.128–129 (roles of Executive Board /
  Chief Services Officer / DG HR, procedural safeguards, appeal routes
  and time-limits).
